WEBVTT

00:00.226 --> 00:03.795
Welcome everybody to this week's Menlo Midweek podcast.

00:03.835 --> 00:04.677
My name is Mark.

00:04.978 --> 00:05.660
My name is Matt.

00:05.780 --> 00:07.605
We've got Christian here from Mobilize Love.

00:07.645 --> 00:08.868
Welcome back, man.

00:08.988 --> 00:10.131
Thank you so much for having me.

00:10.151 --> 00:10.793
Yeah.

00:10.913 --> 00:11.554
I have to be back.

00:11.575 --> 00:13.519
Dude, so it's always great having you in here.

00:13.640 --> 00:16.146
And it's just amazing the stories that it.

00:16.194 --> 00:17.155
you know, mobilize love.

00:17.175 --> 00:19.618
We hear about what the amazing work that you guys are doing.

00:19.658 --> 00:23.822
And so if you're listening to this, this is February 4th.

00:24.083 --> 00:27.346
So we've got about two months until our 4th of Bay 5K.

00:27.687 --> 00:28.167
That's right.

00:28.187 --> 00:28.468
Yeah.

00:28.588 --> 00:30.630
So we're doing this to get it on people's maps.

00:30.670 --> 00:36.557
This is probably the first time people will be hearing about it unless you have recurring reminders to set things up on the website like I do.

00:36.717 --> 00:38.058
So no one else probably has that.

00:38.819 --> 00:42.383
But there is before the Bay 5K web page is live now.

00:42.423 --> 00:45.106
We've officially locked it in for March 28th.

00:45.602 --> 00:50.475
So Matt, let's tee up what for the Bay 5K is and how Christian and Mobilize love are playing a part of that.

00:50.776 --> 00:53.182
Yeah, well, for the Bay 5K is our annual 5K run.

00:53.262 --> 00:56.049
I mean, I say annual, it's our second year doing it.

00:56.230 --> 00:59.298
And I think the only reason we have a second year is because the first year was so fun.

01:00.100 --> 01:02.386
But really, it's an opportunity to

01:02.498 --> 01:10.968
get your friends, neighbors, anyone who likes walking or running out for the day at beautiful Shoreline Park in Mountain View.

01:11.429 --> 01:13.632
It's in what they call the kite flying area.

01:13.672 --> 01:14.653
That's legitimately what it is.

01:14.693 --> 01:20.560
If you search on Google Maps, kite flying area, you will see a shoreline like that's a designated area.

01:21.381 --> 01:25.426
But basically, we're getting together that day as many people as possible to

01:25.474 --> 01:36.248
to be for the bay and what that means is we're supporting local partners and organizations that we're connected to and our premier partner for this event is Mobilized Love.

01:36.268 --> 01:49.906
We were last year as well so we as we've gotten to know the work that Mobilized Love has done it's been great for us to support them in that way and I think similar to like the food kit build we just did recently like I mean yes could you just

01:50.018 --> 01:51.763
give support to an organization?

01:52.024 --> 01:52.846
Well, sure you could.

01:52.886 --> 02:01.933
But what would it look like to actually be a participant in the event together, to get people moving, the adrenaline going, to do something different and fun.

02:01.973 --> 02:03.698
So that's what the 5K is all about.

02:03.746 --> 02:11.179
Um, and it's something that again, we want people to invite their friends, family members to, even if you're not running or walking for the day, which by the way, there is a one K as well.

02:11.299 --> 02:12.801
If you're signing for that.

02:12.821 --> 02:14.765
Yeah, I think that's like more my speed.

02:14.785 --> 02:18.531
I actually might be on the e-bike this year, like just cruising, making sure everything's okay.

02:18.551 --> 02:24.481
But, um, but yeah, the one K is more my speed, but I'd say like, even if you just show up, it's going to be a fun day either way.

02:24.561 --> 02:25.042
So.

02:25.090 --> 02:30.281
Um, so yeah, happy to connect with Mobilize Love this year and, and be a part of this together.

02:30.763 --> 02:35.673
So Christian, for, I mean, you've been a partner with Menlo for quite a number of years now.

02:36.235 --> 02:40.304
If someone's here and about you for the first time right now, who is Mobilize Love?

02:40.384 --> 02:40.985
Who are you?

02:41.005 --> 02:42.007
What's your involvement with them?

02:42.168 --> 02:43.250
And let's get people up to speed.

02:43.586 --> 02:46.531
Yeah, thank you again for your partnership over the years.

02:47.252 --> 02:50.158
Mobileized love exists to show up and give hope.

02:51.039 --> 02:53.263
And the way that we do that is very unique.

02:53.504 --> 03:01.558
We use these outreach trucks and we go to underserved communities and we provide mobile after-school programs and mobile human services.

03:01.678 --> 03:08.530
The after-school programs are for children and the human services are really for anyone in the community where these children live.

03:08.770 --> 03:14.238
And so we have about 14 different trucks right now operating out of two warehouses.

03:14.258 --> 03:20.347
14 sites that we serve in San Francisco, which is where we started in 2017.

03:21.028 --> 03:23.833
And now we have around six sites down the peninsula.

03:24.634 --> 03:31.184
And so we're expanding down here and we have dreams and aspirations to eventually be one day in the East Bay and then in the South Bay.

03:31.885 --> 03:33.747
But right now just San Francisco and the peninsula.

03:34.048 --> 03:38.194
And yeah, I think the main things we do are first,

03:38.466 --> 03:39.668
meet physical needs.

03:40.229 --> 03:45.098
What are the physical needs that families need, especially low-income families?

03:45.158 --> 03:47.783
And so we try to meet the felt needs of families.

03:48.404 --> 03:51.870
And then secondly, teach personal life skills to children.

03:52.311 --> 03:57.641
And so the three things that we teach really are social-emotional learning, literacy, and then the Bible.

03:58.302 --> 03:59.484
So the good news of Jesus.

03:59.665 --> 04:02.610
And so that's what we do.

04:03.010 --> 04:11.604
Um, it's cool because I think when we, when the first couple of times we were talking, you were just in the city and since then you've actually been able to make it down here to onto the peninsula.

04:11.744 --> 04:16.873
And I think one of the, the places that you're located to is that around like lead elementary school over there in San Mateo.

04:17.153 --> 04:17.434
Yeah.

04:17.975 --> 04:18.295
Yeah.

04:18.455 --> 04:27.330
Um, so Menlo's been a, um, very integral part of our history because we started in 2017 and I approached Menlo way back in the day in 2018.

04:27.931 --> 04:29.714
We needed a specific truck.

04:29.858 --> 04:31.561
And no one was really helping us fund it.

04:31.601 --> 04:41.837
And I came over, my wife and I, and we met someone here and just in a moment of desperation over coffee, we're like, listen, we need this specific truck, because this is how we actually teach the kids.

04:41.877 --> 04:43.820
And Menlo funded that for us.

04:44.041 --> 04:47.767
And so we've had that truck operating since 2018 until now.

04:48.668 --> 04:57.362
And most recently, about a year and a half ago, Menlo came back into play and funded our regional food truck.

04:57.474 --> 05:08.818
cool so that's we started to toy with the idea of expanding out of the city down the peninsula but we would need another set of trucks and the food truck is the most requested truck everyone loves the food truck

05:08.930 --> 05:14.983
And so, Menlo came in again and met that need and funded this beautiful food truck.

05:15.043 --> 05:23.801
So, I mean, part of this, you know, four of the way 5K, we'll get to in a second, but you gotta come and just see the truck that you funded because it's phenomenal, it's beautiful.

05:24.583 --> 05:27.749
And when you say 14 trucks are all the trucks the same, are they different?

05:27.950 --> 05:28.811
What are the trucks about?

05:28.912 --> 05:30.034
Yeah, great question.

05:30.114 --> 05:32.719
Definitely, they're all built for different purposes.

05:34.042 --> 05:38.330
We first started, so when we launched, we launched one truck per year.

05:39.151 --> 05:42.378
And not by any design, it just happened to be that way.

05:42.879 --> 05:44.522
But last year, launched three trucks.

05:44.762 --> 05:48.169
And that just speaks to the amount of need that there is in the Bay Area.

05:48.209 --> 05:52.978
But we have a laundry truck, a stage truck, which Menlo helped us fund, food truck.

05:53.154 --> 06:06.791
Storystruck, mobile literacy program, refrigerated truck, distribution truck, a wellness truck, a screen truck, a regional distribution truck, a regional food truck, a barber van, and then two or three other support vehicles.

06:06.991 --> 06:09.674
Dude, pretty soon you're gonna need a truck to remember all the trucks that you have.

06:09.854 --> 06:13.298
I know, I'm starting to lose, I'm starting to lose count in my mind.

06:13.339 --> 06:14.220
I have to visualize.

06:14.240 --> 06:16.963
What do we got?

06:17.163 --> 06:19.506
What I love about that is that

06:20.130 --> 06:33.031
It seems like you are identifying the needs and then kind of creating a solution to get ahead of that or trying to address something that is contextual to the different parts and different regions that you're serving in.

06:33.612 --> 06:45.010
Something that I think would be cool before we kind of look ahead would be, I remember that you shared a story with me once about how when you first showed up to neighborhoods in the city, you weren't greeted

06:45.410 --> 06:46.011
happily.

06:46.031 --> 06:47.214
I'll say it that way.

06:47.715 --> 06:49.860
There is a little bit of like, what are you guys doing here?

06:49.961 --> 06:50.682
Why are you here?

06:50.742 --> 06:52.988
You don't look like us, you don't sound like us, you want to help us.

06:53.008 --> 06:53.850
Like, what's that about?

06:53.910 --> 06:57.819
So can you share kind of if someone's hearing that for the first time?

06:57.879 --> 07:02.610
Like, if can you share that story and kind of mark the progress of from that moment until.

07:02.722 --> 07:03.443
how you receive now.

07:03.823 --> 07:09.490
Yeah, you know, I always say San Francisco or really the Bay Area is kind of like the Hunger Games.

07:10.171 --> 07:12.394
No one really likes to leave their area, their district.

07:12.934 --> 07:17.480
And so, you know, I had primarily been doing work in a specific area in the city.

07:18.682 --> 07:26.932
And when we launched Mobilize Love, there was other parts of the city that, you know, food deserts, housing communities with no resources at all.

07:27.392 --> 07:28.914
And we wanted to go reach them, but

07:28.994 --> 07:29.975
I didn't know these areas.

07:30.015 --> 07:31.096
I never left my district.

07:31.277 --> 07:37.384
And so to go into these places, we were actually advised against going into certain places.

07:37.824 --> 07:41.208
People told us, we don't know you, we don't trust you.

07:41.268 --> 07:45.353
They didn't say those blatantly, but we picked that up.

07:45.493 --> 07:49.017
And others just told us, you're the wrong skin color.

07:49.398 --> 07:51.420
And it's not wise to do this here.

07:51.440 --> 07:56.306
So ultimately, we love to listen to the community.

07:56.514 --> 08:00.140
But if we listened at that point, we would have never gotten going.

08:00.961 --> 08:04.066
Ultimately, we know God asked us to go.

08:04.206 --> 08:07.972
And so we just obeyed and we went out and we had to earn their trust.

08:08.113 --> 08:08.774
And that's all we did.

08:08.814 --> 08:09.835
We kept our mouth shut.

08:10.677 --> 08:12.980
We showed up, we served with no strings attached.

08:13.702 --> 08:18.830
And you know, when we really launched the kids program, it was a week before COVID.

08:19.651 --> 08:21.855
And when we launched the food truck, it was a week before COVID.

08:22.656 --> 08:24.018
And in that moment,

08:24.130 --> 08:34.767
we were able to prove because we didn't stop showing up and we were outdoors and we were safe that we were legit because we earned their trust because a lot of nonprofits couldn't operate.

08:34.968 --> 08:36.210
They couldn't have people indoors.

08:36.650 --> 08:39.575
And we had built this fleet of trucks for outdoor experience.

08:39.956 --> 08:46.186
It's actually, I tell people we were like Noah, we were building this arc, you know, and we didn't know quite why.

08:46.326 --> 08:51.154
And then when COVID hit, we're like, wow, you know, everything we were doing was safe and it was outdoors.

08:51.234 --> 08:59.644
So yeah, from that point until now, now, you know, COVID year was so many communities where like, come to our neighborhood, come to our neighborhood.

08:59.664 --> 09:04.450
And so that really helped us gain a lot of credibility and trust and meet a lot of partners.

09:04.610 --> 09:05.792
You know, we don't do the work alone.

09:05.812 --> 09:10.237
A lot of churches support us, a lot of community nonprofits support us.

09:10.838 --> 09:12.059
And we partner together with them.

09:12.900 --> 09:17.025
But now, yeah, we have more requests than we can actually pull off.

09:17.085 --> 09:19.868
And there's a reputation now.

09:20.409 --> 09:21.170
Yeah.

09:21.474 --> 09:37.313
I think that just speaks to the, like there's something there about being willing to show up even when you're not necessarily welcomed and like being willing to serve people even because they think, folks sometimes think they know what they want but maybe don't know what they need.

09:37.354 --> 09:42.980
And in this case, like you're meeting a need that people may not have even realized or been skeptical of.

09:43.641 --> 09:50.770
And there's a, there's a true servant posture in that that I just think if more of us understood that,

09:50.914 --> 09:58.310
we would be able to, in a good way, infiltrate different areas that we can show up and bring hope to.

09:59.011 --> 10:02.178
Because sometimes we're put off by the idea of like, oh, you don't want this?

10:02.238 --> 10:03.581
OK, no, no, I'll back way off.

10:03.601 --> 10:04.162
I'll back way off.

10:04.202 --> 10:07.269
And the idea that you're saying, no, we feel called.

10:07.670 --> 10:09.714
There's something that

10:09.826 --> 10:11.048
God has directed us towards.

10:11.148 --> 10:11.809
I just love that.

10:12.069 --> 10:17.818
And even in the face of adversity or skepticism, you're still bringing that energy.

10:17.958 --> 10:22.585
And I think more of us need that resiliency in various aspects of our lives.

10:22.605 --> 10:23.746
So thanks for that, man.

10:24.227 --> 10:24.327
Yeah.

10:24.347 --> 10:25.749
And I think it's all about the heart, though.

10:25.950 --> 10:29.114
We didn't have a Messiah complex or Savior complex.

10:29.996 --> 10:34.843
I think once we started to interact with the communities, we let them know, hey, I live in the city.

10:35.484 --> 10:37.106
I'm raising four kids here.

10:37.250 --> 10:39.039
We're actually very much the same.

10:39.220 --> 10:41.009
We're all just dads trying to survive.

10:41.049 --> 10:46.194
And by the way, side note, how else did we get our wives?

10:46.370 --> 10:52.697
You should see how, if you saw a picture of my wife and how beautiful she was, then he took a leg at me.

10:52.717 --> 10:53.818
He'd be like, how in the world?

10:54.319 --> 10:56.521
It's because love just keeps showing up.

10:57.402 --> 10:58.624
Did she want me initially?

10:58.684 --> 10:59.465
No.

11:01.307 --> 11:02.128
You have to earn it.

11:02.428 --> 11:05.592
And then you have to insert your personality.

11:05.612 --> 11:06.953
And then eventually she'll fall in love.

11:06.973 --> 11:09.436
Well, you heard it here first.

11:09.616 --> 11:12.059
Servant leadership for love.

11:12.079 --> 11:12.860
Yeah, yeah, exactly.

11:12.880 --> 11:13.440
Keep showing up.

11:13.561 --> 11:14.802
I love that love shows up.

11:14.882 --> 11:16.925
I'm curious with your tenure in the city.

11:17.405 --> 11:25.076
I'm sure me, like, needs of the city look differently before COVID, look differently during COVID, look differently after COVID.

11:25.617 --> 11:28.841
And then there's this weird AI thing that's happening now that everyone's talking about.

11:29.302 --> 11:32.005
What do you anticipate future needs will be?

11:32.065 --> 11:35.410
And how is that playing into what you guys are doing now?

11:36.546 --> 11:40.113
Well, I like to remind people that Mobilize Love definitely doesn't do it all.

11:40.935 --> 11:43.019
I don't think any work does it all.

11:43.179 --> 11:50.994
I think there's three types of work in ministry, which is relief for those that just need it immediately.

11:51.395 --> 11:55.122
There's development to get people out of where they are.

11:55.490 --> 12:01.883
There's a third one, but I can't remember, but there's whoever works on the systemic stuff, you know, that's way upstream.

12:02.344 --> 12:05.871
So, we don't really do a ton of things systemically.

12:07.073 --> 12:09.839
We're trying to meet the immediate family's needs right now.

12:09.879 --> 12:15.410
The systemic thing we are doing, though, is teaching children personal life skills in literacy.

12:15.522 --> 12:22.410
Because it's around the third grade that pretty much if you look at the numbers, their life has a certain projection.

12:23.071 --> 12:32.902
So that is the systemic thing that we are doing is teaching children to read, having a social emotional tool belt, and have some knowledge of the fact that God loves them and has a plan for their life.

12:33.522 --> 12:36.626
That's the most systemic thing we're doing and it's with children.

12:36.666 --> 12:38.688
So we're not gonna see a lot of fruit from that right away.

12:40.490 --> 12:43.794
But for families like in the future, I mean just economically,

12:43.906 --> 12:47.411
These families need a livable wage and affordable housing.

12:47.431 --> 12:48.733
I mean, that's the most important thing.

12:49.113 --> 12:53.880
The growing divide between the rich and the poor in the Bay Area is a real thing.

12:54.360 --> 12:59.548
I mean, for people to get out of poverty, the first rung of the latter is nine feet high.

13:00.108 --> 13:04.274
So you either are fully dependent on the government for everything.

13:04.578 --> 13:08.884
Or you have to work two to three jobs just to get to where you're at for what you're getting for free.

13:09.205 --> 13:10.927
It's a really broken system.

13:11.128 --> 13:13.471
We need people to go into government and fix those things.

13:13.571 --> 13:14.973
It's way beyond my pay grade.

13:15.735 --> 13:31.718
But what we're called to do is a lot of families are one paycheck away, just one paycheck away, one instance away, one traumatic family event away from a slippery slope of entering into public housing or generational poverty.

13:31.758 --> 13:34.322
And what we're trying to do is avoid that.

13:34.498 --> 13:46.256
And there's got to be something to be said for the families that do have a parent or two parents that are both grinding, hustling, working that much, maybe not having a consistent adult figure in their lives.

13:46.316 --> 13:58.234
When you show up consistently, you are taking a lot of different responsibility there, both in provision of resources or teaching, but also almost guidance and mentorship.

13:58.915 --> 14:03.442
I'm sure there's got to be some great stories in there around you, your consistent presence,

14:03.746 --> 14:06.529
making a difference in that community and neighborhood as well.

14:07.631 --> 14:08.171
Yeah, there are.

14:08.231 --> 14:11.516
I mean, there's dozens of stories of just families.

14:11.536 --> 14:16.502
I think the first pillar of our work really is establishing presence.

14:16.582 --> 14:19.986
I think there is no hack for human connection.

14:20.046 --> 14:28.817
So I think with the whole AI thing and innovating for the future, and I love all that stuff, you know, it's making our lives easier with technology.

14:28.977 --> 14:33.202
But the one hack is that that'll never be

14:33.826 --> 14:37.714
figured out is human connection, you know, and it's getting worse actually.

14:37.854 --> 14:40.940
The loneliness epidemic and kids wandering around.

14:40.960 --> 14:43.004
I mean, they're just wandering around and floating.

14:43.725 --> 14:47.813
And what we like to say is whoever's going to show up in their life is going to win the battle of influence.

14:48.635 --> 14:56.370
And so if we don't show up and they, all they behold are the guys on the street and what their, the activities they're up to, they'll be that.

14:56.546 --> 14:58.449
Because kids become what they behold.

14:58.489 --> 15:00.152
And so if that's all they see, they'll do that.

15:00.713 --> 15:05.360
And so we need someone positive to enter into the world, model something different.

15:05.380 --> 15:10.048
That's why a lot of what we do, we take them on outings, get out of their zip code, look at the world.

15:10.328 --> 15:12.772
That's why also literacy, read this book.

15:12.793 --> 15:16.178
Frederick Douglass said, once a child learns to read, he's forever free.

15:16.322 --> 15:21.952
And so it's to just change their perspective That's why we do a lot of sports games.

15:21.992 --> 15:30.166
That's why we do a lot of summer camps It's just to show them a different perspective and and all of that is Something you can't hack with technology.

15:30.206 --> 15:41.906
You got to show up in the world earn their trust have enough relational equity to have the parents sign a permission slip and then Be super present when we're with them

15:42.146 --> 16:04.658
Yeah and it's cool to see the ripple effect of that as well where because of that trust and because of that consistency not only have you been able to be more present in that community but also your sphere is growing as well whether that's in you know relationship with them or in proximity where now you've been able to be further and further away from where you guys started and it's cool to see the impact that you're making and yeah the

16:04.866 --> 16:12.119
the stories that we've heard from when we'd have people from our congregation show up and see you guys at Lead Elementary School down San Mateo.

16:12.159 --> 16:13.562
Like, oh, it's so fun, man.

16:13.842 --> 16:15.285
Yeah, you guys are doing amazing work.

16:15.325 --> 16:25.042
And so Matt, I'm curious for you as we're looking forward to this event that we're putting on second year in a row for the Bay 5K.

16:25.538 --> 16:32.687
when we are trying to select someone to say, hey, we're putting this on so that we can help resource you.

16:32.707 --> 16:35.471
What gets you excited, specifically, about mobileized love?

16:35.611 --> 16:37.874
And why are we like, yes, let's go ahead.

16:38.114 --> 16:39.375
And like, these are our guys.

16:39.576 --> 16:52.752
Yeah, I mean, I think to back to kind of a lot of what Christians share, just it's such a worthy cause to invest in the life of children.

16:52.812 --> 16:54.034
They are the most

16:54.210 --> 16:59.897
they're the population with the most potential, and yet they are the most vulnerable to so many different things.

17:00.077 --> 17:05.204
And so I know that intuitively now as a parent, but I also see it.

17:05.344 --> 17:09.809
I bring my youngest into class every morning.

17:10.230 --> 17:13.194
He doesn't take transportation or bus or anything.

17:13.214 --> 17:16.818
We drive him and I'll walk into the schoolyard.

17:16.962 --> 17:18.425
So I love growing up on the East Coast.

17:18.626 --> 17:21.191
We just didn't have open school yards like they have in California.

17:21.212 --> 17:23.617
Like here, there's like common areas.

17:23.657 --> 17:26.924
Ours was like, go into this hole, this dark hole.

17:27.105 --> 17:29.149
But this is like, this place is amazing.

17:29.189 --> 17:31.735
But when I walk, I see the kids interacting with each other.

17:31.755 --> 17:36.626
And it's like, almost you could sort of read the ways in which they are

17:36.706 --> 17:44.697
trying to find their footing in this world, whether it is socially, whether it is emotionally, academically, like there are just a lot of different pressures.

17:44.877 --> 18:06.386
And in the Bay Area, the performative nature of the Bay Area, and the microcosm that this place is economically as well, that is the growing disparity, like there are additional layers of pressure in this place that I think necessitate our awareness on how to meet

18:06.466 --> 18:08.250
the needs of young people.

18:08.671 --> 18:13.182
And I'm just aware of that, my awareness is increasing as we go on.

18:13.202 --> 18:21.522
So I think if you're listening to this, or you have kids, or maybe you don't, but you resonate with what's being shared.

18:21.602 --> 18:27.087
This is a great opportunity to spend a Saturday where you're giving back a little bit and you're having some fun in the process.

18:28.048 --> 18:32.391
Last year, one of the things I loved out last year, because I wasn't in the planning process for the Bay 5K.

18:32.411 --> 18:37.416
I just got assigned a couple different roles, like most of our staff does, of, hey, you're directing cars to go park.

18:37.436 --> 18:38.437
I was like, cool, that's great.

18:38.457 --> 18:40.238
I'll stand in the front and help park some cars.

18:40.639 --> 18:51.588
But then when I finally got up there and saw where the starting line was, and I saw the video truck, and I saw the food truck, and I had a bowl, a rice bowl with, I think it was pork, like shredded pork or chicken,

18:51.568 --> 18:53.250
It was delicious, first of all.

18:53.411 --> 19:07.750
And then the physical presence of these trucks and the colorful and engaging nature of them, like you show up in a way that demands attention.

19:08.311 --> 19:16.122
And if I saw that at my school, in the same way the TV would get wheeled into the classroom when I was a kid, I'd be like, oh, this is kind of cool.

19:16.142 --> 19:19.186
We got a TV coming in to see that.

19:19.394 --> 19:21.758
at a school has got to be so exciting for a kid.

19:22.179 --> 19:31.115
And so like when I got to the 5K, I was finally able to conceptualize what you're all doing and how you're showing up in that way.

19:31.516 --> 19:38.368
And even I think I attended a couple months ago an event that you had in Redwood City where the, is it the literacy truck, library truck, is that what you call it?

19:38.388 --> 19:38.869
Stories truck.

19:38.889 --> 19:39.570
Stories truck.

19:39.874 --> 19:40.735
That thing was so cool.

19:40.796 --> 19:41.957
It was like a library on wheels.

19:42.458 --> 19:48.007
And libraries are becoming fewer and farther between in existence now anyway, with computers and everything.

19:48.729 --> 19:52.515
And you could hop up there and pull one of the many children's books that are there.

19:52.595 --> 19:53.897
It's well lit.

19:53.937 --> 19:56.241
It's almost like the top is natural light coming through.

19:56.321 --> 19:57.844
It was just so beautiful.

19:57.884 --> 20:06.578
And so I'm like, this is exactly a pathway for kids to find things to connect to.

20:06.658 --> 20:09.061
that will provide investment in their lives.

20:09.121 --> 20:12.645
And so for any listener for any here, this is a worthy cause.

20:12.725 --> 20:14.647
It's worth the Saturday and it's worth your support.

20:14.747 --> 20:21.015
So getting more people to know that there are good works being done in the midst of a challenging world.

20:21.775 --> 20:22.717
Who's in a fan of that?

20:25.279 --> 20:29.064
Christian, it seems like you're very like, let's just do it, go get her kind of a guy.

20:29.104 --> 20:31.687
And obviously that's kind of how this whole thing got started.

20:31.727 --> 20:34.450
And so if someone needs a little bit of encouragement,

20:34.722 --> 20:43.554
that's listening to this, whether that is going to your website, donating, whether that is heading to four of the Bay 5K, sign up for that.

20:45.217 --> 20:55.992
What do you think can change in someone from maybe if they're not serving in anything at all, but they know that they're feeling like, man, I think that God wants me to make a difference, and maybe this is one option that they can.

20:56.813 --> 21:00.598
How would you encourage someone to say, okay, I'm ready to take that step.

21:00.939 --> 21:03.442
I just need a little bit of something.

21:04.194 --> 21:13.525
Yeah, well, first and foremost, I would say that by our design, by God, we are built and created to give away to others.

21:14.025 --> 21:16.848
It's just in our nature, it's in our DNA.

21:16.868 --> 21:26.099
And unless we do it, there will always be a low grade of frustration in our life of just never having enough.

21:26.319 --> 21:28.882
Something seems off.

21:28.994 --> 21:36.024
I remember one time my wife and I were in this like a week of like arguing over and over and over about silly things.

21:36.065 --> 21:41.633
And I just turned her and I said, you know what, we need to just go get our eyes off ourself and let's go serve people.

21:42.955 --> 21:46.841
And I tell you, you know, we stopped arguing right away.

21:46.861 --> 21:54.752
I'm not saying serving will heal your marriage, but I'm saying though it changes your perspective when you get your eyes off yourself and you serve others.

21:55.153 --> 21:56.134
Because that's who Jesus is.

21:56.635 --> 21:58.578
The Bible says in John, I think 13,

21:58.786 --> 22:02.111
when finally Jesus realized all authority had been given to him.

22:02.131 --> 22:06.538
They're at the Last Supper and the Bible says, and Jesus realized all authority was given to him.

22:08.100 --> 22:21.821
The next verse says, the thing that he did with all of his authority, first of all, I don't know what you would do if the moment God gave you all authority, but I would immediately go, nine or super bowl and a house on the marina green dropped 25 pounds.

22:21.841 --> 22:23.844
That's what I would do with the authority God gave me.

22:24.465 --> 22:27.730
So carnal, sorry, so selfish, but Jesus

22:27.842 --> 22:34.652
Knowing all authority got up put a towel around his waist and washes disciples feet And that's our rabbi.

22:34.672 --> 22:35.433
That's our teacher.

22:35.493 --> 22:52.998
That's the one we model our life after and what he's showing is when you've been given a Healthy mind see some of you think I'm where I am because I made great decisions and I'm a I'm a go-getter Yeah, but where did you get that healthy mind from because some people deal with mental illness?

22:54.100 --> 22:55.762
Okay, you have a healthy body and

22:55.874 --> 22:57.176
Some people deal with disease.

22:57.597 --> 23:01.543
Like all these things were graced to you and God gave them to you.

23:01.583 --> 23:06.972
So you have affluence, you have influence, you have position, you have authority for what to use on yourself.

23:07.874 --> 23:10.138
No, so you can leverage it to serve others.

23:10.238 --> 23:22.578
And I would truly with 27 years of ministry experience say this, that the happiest people I know, the most joyful, the most fulfilled are people that use everything they have for others and not themselves.

23:22.754 --> 23:31.353
And the most frustrated people I know that seemingly have everything But they're kind of selfish with it and I'm not just talking about money.

23:31.373 --> 23:36.224
I'm talking about their time and their energy And like only focused on their kids and that's it.

23:36.485 --> 23:39.872
It's like there's something off about you, you know, I'm not judging.

23:39.892 --> 23:40.754
I'm just saying

23:40.898 --> 23:42.261
You seem frustrated.

23:42.862 --> 23:45.588
So I would lovingly just say, you can do something.

23:45.849 --> 23:48.134
No one can do it all, but you can do something.

23:48.856 --> 23:57.074
And I'll tell you one last little analogy I used, but I'm in charge of my family's laundry, and we have four children, and then my wife and I, so there's six of us.

23:57.154 --> 24:00.857
And I love doing the laundry because it's the only thing in my life I can fully control.

24:01.578 --> 24:04.521
I can't control anything else, but I can dominate laundry.

24:04.541 --> 24:05.722
All authority has been given to you.

24:05.742 --> 24:06.623
All authority has been given to me.

24:06.643 --> 24:08.084
In the laundry realm.

24:08.104 --> 24:08.885
So I'm a cold baby.

24:08.905 --> 24:10.567
I love it.

24:10.607 --> 24:11.567
I take joy in it.

24:11.608 --> 24:13.750
I take pride that I do and I'm on it.

24:14.630 --> 24:20.156
But there are some Fridays where I look at the pile and it's just too big and I'm like, you know what I do in that moment?

24:20.176 --> 24:21.817
I shut the door and I ignore it.

24:22.318 --> 24:24.019
And I feel like a lot of people do that in the Bay Area.

24:24.039 --> 24:24.760
It's too much.

24:25.320 --> 24:26.381
The problems are too much.

24:26.441 --> 24:27.122
We know.

24:27.586 --> 24:28.808
It's like systemic.

24:29.068 --> 24:30.530
It's not just political.

24:30.710 --> 24:32.233
It's socioeconomic.

24:32.373 --> 24:33.975
It's sin.

24:34.095 --> 24:35.157
It's all these things.

24:35.177 --> 24:37.680
And so we look at all of it and we just say, you know what?

24:38.501 --> 24:39.423
That's a little too much.

24:39.463 --> 24:41.305
And we perverbally just shut the door and ignore it.

24:41.325 --> 24:43.709
And then we just medicate and entertain ourselves to death.

24:43.989 --> 24:47.514
And what I'm going to say is just open the door a little bit.

24:47.995 --> 24:50.258
Just grab a couple pieces of clothing and just fold them.

24:50.754 --> 24:53.717
So that's what this for the Bay 5K does.

24:53.797 --> 24:54.417
I'm not a runner.

24:54.457 --> 24:54.858
Look at me.

24:54.998 --> 24:55.859
I'm not built to run.

24:55.979 --> 25:00.243
I'm built to be on a beach cruiser bike, you know, and get a burrito.

25:00.623 --> 25:01.564
That's how I'm built.

25:01.584 --> 25:06.229
But I know that it's not about me.

25:06.689 --> 25:12.915
These kids, if I can spend half a day run and it would benefit one child, it's worth it.

25:12.955 --> 25:14.597
It's the best way to spend a Saturday.

25:14.917 --> 25:16.618
Yeah, that's so good.

25:16.638 --> 25:20.402
I'm piggybacking off that laundry analogy real quick because

25:20.834 --> 25:28.986
authority has not been given to me for laundry, but in my house now that everybody's of age, everybody pretty much does their own laundry, which is awesome.

25:29.066 --> 25:40.082
And what I have come to appreciate about that is now everyone has a stake in how the laundry gets done and what they're willing to put into it.

25:40.258 --> 25:43.304
the level in which they will have clean clothing to wear.

25:44.105 --> 25:48.273
And all of that depends solely on their effort and initiative and what they're willing to do.

25:48.413 --> 25:53.042
And occasionally, there is a day where my kids will come to me and be like, I don't have anything to wear it.

25:53.102 --> 25:56.107
I'll look inside the thing and I'll be like, man, that piled up pretty quick, didn't it?

25:56.548 --> 25:59.333
And I think in those moments, we help each other out and lift each other up.

25:59.393 --> 26:01.938
But I think what I'm trying to say is like,

26:02.050 --> 26:07.978
everyone has an opportunity to make a valuable contribution, no matter where you are for something like this.

26:08.058 --> 26:17.250
Like, even if you think the problem is so big, like, yeah, but you might only have just like one load of laundry to do, like, and this is, this is like that first step is to, is to do that.

26:17.350 --> 26:20.895
So, yeah, this is just the whole thing kind of, kind of sticks with me.

26:20.955 --> 26:26.482
Now, I really want to know how high on the priority list is an

26:26.594 --> 26:32.786
ice cream truck for mobilizing because if it's on the list i would just say as someone who

26:32.930 --> 26:34.352
who knows ice cream.

26:34.633 --> 26:38.438
I worked for a Carville ice cream on the East Coast for three years at 15 years old.

